---
// FACTS — interesting facts about Pluto.
// Seeded issues:
//   * deprecated <marquee> scrolling element     (marquee)
//   * <dl> with an invalid child element          (definition-list)
//   * low-contrast intro text                     (color-contrast)
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Pluto Facts" description="Surprising and interesting facts about the dwarf planet Pluto.">
  <h1>Interesting Pluto Facts</h1>

  <!-- Low-contrast intro paragraph (color-contrast) -->
  <p class="muted-fail">
    Small, distant, and deeply strange — Pluto keeps surprising the scientists
    who study it. Here are some of the most remarkable things we know.
  </p>

  <!-- Deprecated scrolling marquee element (marquee) -->
  <marquee behavior="scroll" direction="left">
    ☃ It snows on Pluto — but the snow is red! ☃ A year on Pluto lasts 248 Earth years ☃ Pluto has mountains made of water ice ☃
  </marquee>

  <h2>A heart on its surface</h2>
  <p>
    Pluto's most famous feature is a vast, bright, heart-shaped region now called
    Tombaugh Regio. Its left lobe, Sputnik Planitia, is a 1,000-km-wide plain of
    nitrogen ice that slowly churns and resurfaces itself.
  </p>

  <h2>Fast facts</h2>
  <!-- Definition list containing an invalid child (<p>) — definition-list rule -->
  <dl>
    <dt>Smaller than you think</dt>
    <dd>Pluto is only about two-thirds the width of Earth's Moon.</dd>
    <dt>A long, long year</dt>
    <dd>Pluto takes 248 Earth years to orbit the Sun once. It has not completed a single orbit since it was discovered in 1930.</dd>
    <dt>Five moons</dt>
    <dd>Charon, Styx, Nix, Kerberos, and Hydra.</dd>
    <p>All of these facts come from a combination of telescope observations and the 2015 New Horizons flyby.</p>
  </dl>

  <h2>More strange truths</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Pluto's atmosphere is blue, just like Earth's, though for different reasons.</li>
    <li>From Pluto, the Sun would look like a very bright star, not a disc.</li>
    <li>Pluto and its moon Charon always show each other the same face — they are mutually tidally locked.</li>
    <li>Pluto is one of the most reflective bodies in the Solar System, because its surface is coated in fresh ice.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
